******
[1] Victoria
Date: Sat 10 Jan 2015
Source: Melbourne Herald Sun [edited]
http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/victoria/babies-most-at-risk-of-whooping-cough/story-fni0fit3-1227180816224


Whooping cough cases shot up by more than 50 percent in the past year with an alarming increase in babies diagnosed with the potentially deadly infection. There were 4606 cases of whooping cough, also known as pertussis, between January 2014-2015. The largest increases were in children aged 10-14 and babies under 6 months. In a warning to clinicians and public health personnel, Chief Health Officer Rosemary Lester said infants of this age were also the most susceptible to the severe complications of pertussis. One in every 200 babies that contracts the infection will die.

The latest data from the [Victoria] Department of Health showed a 43 percent increase in whooping cough cases in patients aged 10-14 to 6 Jan 2015. There was also a 38 percent rise in babies aged under 6 months, increasing to 76 cases in 2014 from 55 in 2013.

[Byline: Lucie Vandenberg]

